feature.name: appClientSupport-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the Liberty server to process client modules and support remote client containers.

feature.name: appSecurity-1.0
feature.description: This feature is superseded by appSecurity-2.0. Support for securing the server runtime environment and applications. This feature enables servlet-3.0 and web application security, support for LDAP and basic user registries, and SSL. To support secure EJB applications, you must add the ejbLite-3.1 feature. When you add this feature to your server, you need to configure a user registry, such as the basic user registry or the LDAP user registry.

feature.name: appSecurity-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for securing the server runtime environment and applications; it includes a basic user registry. This feature supersedes appSecurity-1.0 and does not include servlet-3.0 or support for the LDAP user registry. To secure web applications, add the servlet-3.0 feature. To secure EJB applications, add the ejbLite-3.1 feature. To use LDAP, add the ldapRegistry-3.0 feature. When you add the appSecurity-2.0 feature to your server, you need to configure a user registry, such as the basic user registry or the LDAP user registry.

feature.name: appSecurityClient-1.0
feature.description: Support for securing the client container runtime environment and applications. This feature enables application security, CSIv2 and SSL on the client.

feature.name: com.ibm.websphere.appserver.autoRestConnector-2.0
feature.description: %description

feature.name: batch-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Java Batch 1.0 API specified by JSR-352.

feature.name: beanValidation-1.1
feature.description: The Bean Validation 1.1 specification provides an annotation based model for validating JavaBeans. It can be used to assert and maintain the integrity of data as it travels through an application.

feature.name: bells-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of Basic Extensions using Liberty Libraries (BELL).

feature.name: cdi-1.2
feature.description: The Contexts and Dependency Injection specification makes it easier to integrate Java EE components of different types. It provides a common mechanism to inject component such as EJBs or Managed Beans into other components such as JSPs or other EJBs.

feature.name: concurrent-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the creation of managed executors that allow applications to submit tasks to run concurrently, with thread context that is managed by the application server.It also enables the creation of managed thread factories to create threads that run with the threadcontext of the component that looks up the managed thread factory.

feature.name: distributedMap-1.0
feature.displayName: Distributed Map interface for Dynamic Caching
feature.description: This feature provides a local cache service which can be accessed through the DistributedMap API. A default cache is bound in JNDI at "services/cache/distributedmap". Caches can be distributed through addition of a network cache provider such as WebSphere eXtreme Scale.

feature.name: ejb-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for Enterprise JavaBeans written to the EJB 3.2 specification.

feature.name: ejbHome-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables the use of home interfaces in Enterprise JavaBeans.

feature.name: ejbLite-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for Enterprise JavaBeans written to the EJB Lite subset of the EJB 3.2 specification.

feature.name: ejbPersistentTimer-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables the use of persistent timers in Enterprise JavaBeans.

feature.name: ejbRemote-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables the use of remote interfaces in Enterprise JavaBeans.

feature.name: el-3.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Expression Language (EL) 3.0.

feature.name: federatedRegistry-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for federation of multiple user registries.

feature.name: j2eeManagement-1.1
feature.description: This feature allows applications to utilize the interfaces defined in the JSR77 specification.

feature.name: jacc-1.5
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java Authorization Contract for Containers (JACC) version 1.5 In order to add the jacc-1.5 feature to your server, you need to add the third party JACC provider which is not a part of the WebSphere Application Server Liberty profile.

feature.name: jaspic-1.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for securing the server runtime environment and applications using Java Authentication SPI for Containers (JASPIC) providers as defined in JSR-196

feature.name: javaMail-1.5
feature.description: This feature allows applications to utilize the JavaMail 1.5 API.

feature.name: javaee-7.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support the Java EE 7.0 Full Platform.

feature.name: javaeeClient-7.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java EE 7 Application Client.

feature.name: jaxb-2.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Java Architecture for XML Binding 2.2 specification, which provides easy mapping of Java classes to XML documents.

feature.name: jaxrs-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java API for RESTful Web Services. JAX-RS annotations can be used to define web service clients and endpoints that comply with the REST architectural style. Endpoints are accessed through a common interface that is based on the HTTP standard methods.

feature.name: jaxrsClient-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java Client API for JAX-RS 2.0.

feature.name: jaxws-2.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java API for XML-Based Web Services 2.2. JAX-WS web services and clients communicate using XML. Annotations can be used to simplify the development of JAX-WS clients and endpoints.

feature.name: jca-1.7
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of resource adapters to access Enterprise Information Systems (EIS) from applications. The configuration of a resource adapter also includes the configuration of connection factories, administered objects and activation specifications. Any resource adapter that complies with the JCA 1.7 specification or lower can be used. High performance connection pooling is also provided.

feature.name: jcaInboundSecurity-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables security inflow for resource adapters.

feature.name: jdbc-4.1
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of DataSources to access Databases from applications. Any JDBC driver that complies with the JDBC 4.1, 4.0, 3.0, or 2.x specification can be used; customized configuration of many specific providers is included. High performance connection pooling is also provided.

feature.name: jndi-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the use of Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) to access server configured resources such as DataSources or JMS Connection Factories. It also allows access to Java primitives configured in the server as a jndiEntry.

feature.name: jpa-2.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for applications that use application-managed and container-managed JPA written to the Java Persistence API 2.1 specification. The support is built on top of EclipseLink to support the container-managed programming model.

feature.name: jpaContainer-2.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for applications that use application-managedand container-managed JPA written to the Java Persistence API 2.1 specification. This only includes Java Persistence API 2.1 specification interfaces, and container-managedJPA integration. This feature does not include any JPA implementation.

feature.name: jsf-2.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for web applications that use the Java Server Faces (JSF) 2.2 framework. This framework simplifies the construction of user interfaces.

feature.name: json-1.0
feature.description: This feature provides access to the JavaScript Object Notation (JSON4J) library. The JSON4J library provides a simple Java model for constructing and manipulating data to be rendered as JSON data.

feature.name: jsonp-1.0
feature.description: The Java API for JSON Processing (JSON-P) feature provides a standardized method for constructing and manipulating data to be rendered in JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).

feature.name: jsp-2.3
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java Server Pages (JSPs) that are written to the JSP 2.3 specification. This framework simplifies the construction of user interfaces. Enabling this feature also enables the Expression Language (EL) version 3.0 feature.

feature.name: ldapRegistry-3.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for using an LDAP server as a user registry. Any server that supports LDAP Version 3.0 may be used. Multiple LDAP registries can be configured, and then federated to achieve a single logical registry view.

feature.name: localConnector-1.0
feature.description: This feature allows the use of a local JMX connector that is built into the JVM to access JMX resources in the server. The JMX connector can only be used on the same host machine by a client that has the same user ID and the same JDK as the server process. It enables local access by JMX clients such as jConsole, or other JMX clients that use the Attach API.

feature.name: managedBeans-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Managed Beans 1.0 specification. Managed Beans provide a common foundation for different Java EE components types that are managed by a container. Common services provided to Managed Beans include resource injection, lifecycle management and the use of interceptors.

feature.name: mdb-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables the use of Message-Driven Enterprise JavaBeans written to the EJB 3.2 specification. MDBs allow asynchronous processing of messages within a Java EE component.

feature.name: microProfile-1.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support the Micro Profile for enterprise Java.

feature.name: monitor-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the Performance Monitoring Infrastructure (PMI) for other features the server is running. Monitoring data is accessible through standard MXBeans; access through the traditional WebSphere Perf MBean can be enabled.

feature.name: passwordUtilities-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for obtaining the values of the user and password attributes of authData elements from an application, and also allows the use of the com.ibm.websphere.crypto.PasswordUtil class as an API.

feature.name: restConnector-2.0
feature.description: A secure admin connector that can be used locally or remotely using any JDK. It enables remote access by clients via a REST-based connector and requires SSL and basic user security configuration. Client support includes JMX. This feature supersedes the restConnector-1.0 feature and does not include the jaxrs-1.1 feature.

feature.name: servlet-3.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for HTTP Servlets written to the Java Servlet 3.1 specification. You can package servlets in Java EE specified WAR or EAR files. If servlet security is required, you should also configure an appSecurity feature. Without a security feature, any security constraints for the application are ignored.

feature.name: ssl-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) connections. The secure HTTPS listener is not started unless the ssl-1.0 feature is enabled and a keystore is configured.

feature.name: wasJmsClient-2.0
feature.description: The wasJmsClient-2.0 feature provides applications with access to the message queues that are hosted on WebSphere Application Server through the JMS 2.0 API. This feature supersedes wasJmsClient-1.1. The wasJmsClient-2.0 feature is compliant with JMS 2.0 specifications and is supported only on JDK 7 or later. It enables access to the messaging engine that is enabled through the wasJmsServer feature, and also to the service integration bus that is hosted on a full profile server.

feature.name: wasJmsSecurity-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the WebSphere Embedded Messaging Server to authenticate and authorize access from JMS clients.

feature.name: wasJmsServer-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables an embedded messaging server that is JMS compliant. Applications can send and receive messages using the wasJmsClient feature.

feature.name: webProfile-7.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support the Java EE 7.0 Web Profile.

feature.name: websocket-1.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for WebSocket applications written to the Java API for WebSocket 1.1 specification.
